# Decide legacy memory retirement

## Step

Settle the fate of the old memory stack as ONE migration: Typesense
`memory_observations` (28,050 docs, 99.26% stale, still answering
`joelclaw recall`), the reflect/promote/proposal functions pointed at a
`~/.joelclaw/workspace/MEMORY.md` that doesn't exist, the generic voice
`recall` tool reading the stale index, and the MEM/FRIC suites protecting
all of it. Questions to grill: does `joelclaw recall` retarget to the
Brain/session archive or die; is the stale index archived or deleted; do
the zombie Inngest functions unregister; what happens to the suites; and
what's the deprecation order so nothing user-facing breaks mid-swap.
Evidence: [periphery survey](../memory-system-review/periphery-survey.svx)
flags #3, with per-store receipts in its sections.

## Decision (Joel, 2026-07-17, grilled live)

One migration, one PR, one rollback point:

1. **Retarget `joelclaw recall`** to the Brain/observation stores — the
   command name is good muscle memory and voice already uses the verb.
   The generic voice `recall` tool follows the same retarget.
2. **Archive `memory_observations` to NAS** as a snapshot, then drop it
   from the live Typesense index. Archive-before-delete per the standing
   verify-data-elsewhere rule.
3. **Unregister the zombie Inngest functions** (reflect/promote/proposal
   pointed at the nonexistent `~/.joelclaw/workspace/MEMORY.md`).
4. **Delete the MEM/FRIC suites** with the machinery they protect.

Deprecation order: retarget recall first (user-facing surface never
breaks), then archive+drop the index, then unregister functions and
delete suites. Execution deserves its own step/effort; this decision is
final.
